nglish, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Guillaume","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Germanic.  See  <b>William</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"William","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Guillaume I de Joigny was born in 1158, in France, his father, Renard de Joigny IV, was 38 and his mother, Adèle de Nevers, was 13. He had at least 1 daughter with Beatrix de Sancerre. He died on 15 February 1221, at the age of 63."},"et":{"1158–15 February 1221":"1158–15. veebruar 1221","1154–Male":"1154–Surnud","1157–1209":"1157–1209","1158–1221":"1158–1221","1161–1237":"1161–1237","–1226":"–1226","–1245":"–1245","1192–1247":"1192–1247","–Female":"Surnud","1222–1252":"1222–1252","1120–1179":"1120–1179","1145–1192":"1145–1192","1154":"1154","1120":"1120","1252":"1252","1161":"1161","15 February 1221":"15. veebruar 1221","1192":"1192","1226":"1226","1237":"1237","1247":"1247","1158":"1158","1179":"1179","1245":"1245","1157":"1157","1145":"1145","1222":"1222","1221":"1221","1209":"1209","Joigny, Yonne, Burgundy, France":"Joigny, Yonne, Bourgogne-Franche-Comté, Prantsusmaa","France":"P